Title: The Thalamus of the Macaca Mulatta

@BrainMaps_Delineation.Citation: "The nomenclature used below is based on that of A.E. Walker. Preference has been given to Latin names as the use of English names may easily lead to misunderstanding. The modifiers of the same nucleus are always arranged in such a manner that the first one expresses the first specification, and each following one limits the meaning one step further." (p.17)

@InterMapRelations.Citation: "The nomenclature used below is based on that of A. E. Walker." (p. 17) ... "When the existing and recognized subdivisions were found to be insufficient, and striking morphological differences forced recognition of new units, these have been held within the limits of nuclei recognized by previous authors, reference has been given to Walker's subdivisions." (p. 31)

"The nomenclature used below is based on that of A. E. Walker." (p. 17) ... "When the existing and recognized subdivisions were found to be insufficient, and striking morphological differences forced recognition of new units, these have been held within the limits of nuclei recognized by previous authors, reference has been given to Walker's subdivisions." (p. 31)

"A dense elongated cell group (Plate XLII), which lies just medial to the borderline, seems to bee identical with thal named pulvinar x by Papez and Aronson... However, as no exact position of these groups ... has been reported, ... its description in connection with, and as a part of, the nucleus medialis dorsalis has seemed the best temporary solution."

"Finally, the ventro-medial corner of the nucleus ventralis lateralis, on the basis of its cytoarchitecture, must be delineated as the pars medialis (pars ventralis and pars medialis of Papez and Aronson)."
@InterMapRelations.Comments:
It is not stated clearly in the citation above, to which thalamic nucleus the pars ventralis and medialis, of Papez and Aronson, belong.
In the context of the ventral nuclei the nucleus ventralis is selected.

@InterMapRelations.Citation: "It is customary to subdivide the nucleus ventralis posterior in the ventral posterior medialis and ventral posterior lateralis..."
"It is customary to subdivide the nucleus ventralis posterior in the ventral posterior medialis and ventral posterior lateralis..."
"A small group of cells, which morphological seem to belong to the nucleus ventralis lateralis ... is called pars postrema. This pars is called by Walker nucleus lateralis posterior, pars angularis."

"... we see in the nucleus reuniens small groups of larger and more compactly arrganged cells. The largest of these groups has been given the name nucleus subfascicularis magnocellularis by Papez and Aronson. It has been delineated under this name on Plate XXII."

"The portion of the nucleus [ventralis anteriro] adjacent to the mamillothalamic tract and extending dorsalward along the ventral border of the nucleus anterior ventralis must be delineated as pars magnocellularis (pars submedia of Papez and Aronson)."
"A small group of cells, which morphological seems to belong to the nucleus ventralis lateralis... is called pars postrema. This pars is called by Walker nucleus lateralis posterior, pars angularis."
"The nucleus ventralis intermedius, as described by Crouch, corresponds to the pars oralis of the nucleus ventralis posterior lateralis of this atlas."
